    "instructions": "Perform the following derivation: \n1. Define the standard Unruh temperature: $T_U(a) = \\frac{\\hbar a}{2\\pi c k_B}$.\n2. Define the de Sitter-modified Unruh temperature $T_{dS}(a)$ in the context of MOND/cosmological acceleration $a_0$. Note that in many MOND-related cosmological models, the effective acceleration is modified by the de Sitter horizon or the scale $a_0$ (where $a_0 \\approx c H_0$). Specifically, look for the relation where the temperature is modified by the presence of the cosmological constant or the de Sitter background, often expressed as $T_{dS}(a) = \\frac{\\hbar \\sqrt{a^2 + a_0^2}}{2\\pi c k_B}$ or similar, depending on the specific theoretical framework requested.\n3. Derive the ratio $R = \\frac{T_U(a)}{T_{dS}(a)}$.\n4. Provide the exact algebraic identity and discuss the limit as $a \\to a_0$ and $a \\gg a_0$.",
